SIMPLE: ingenious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ingenious
<hw>In*gen"ious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ingeniosus</ets>, fr. <ets>ingenium</ets> innate or natural
quality, natural capacity, genius: cf. F. <ets>ing⟦eacute⟧nieux</ets>.
See <er>Engine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Possessed of genius, or the
faculty of invention; skillful or promp to invent; having an aptitude to
contrive, or to form new combinations; <as>as, an <ex>ingenious</ex>
author, mechanic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man . . . very wise and <qex>ingenious</qex> in feats of
war.</q> <rj><qau>Hakluyt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou, king, send out⟦br⟧
For torturers <qex>ingenious</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more <qex>ingenious</qex> men are, the more apt are they to
trouble themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proceeding from, pertaining to, or characterized by,
genius or ingenuity; of curious design, structure, or mechanism; <as>as,
an <ex>ingenious</ex> model, or machine; an <ex>ingenious</ex> scheme,
contrivance, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus men go wrong with an <qex>ingenious</qex> skill.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Witty; shrewd; adroit; keen; sagacious; <as>as, an
<ex>ingenious</ex> reply</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mental; intellectual.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A course of learning and <qex>ingenious</qex> studies.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ingeniously</ent>⟦br⟧
